ic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Timezone-aware scheduling produces correct run times across DST spring-forward and fall-back transitions","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is entirely in the next-run-time calculation algorithm's handling of DST-aware datetimes — does it skip the non-existent 2:30 AM, does it pick the right side of the ambiguous 2:30 AM? This is a property of the calculation function, not of cross-module wiring. REAL-INFRA: DST data is embedded in timezone libraries (pytz/zoneinfo); no OS calls or network needed. MOCK-HIDE: Timezone libraries are deterministic and should not be mocked. INTEGRATION-CHECK (down-test): Call the next-run-time calculator with a timezone-aware start time that straddles a DST boundary — no module wiring required. Unit is correct.","test_description":"Call the next-run-time calculator with a schedule of '30 2 * * *' (2:30 AM daily) using a timezone with a known DST transition (e.g., America/New_York). For the spring-forward night (clocks skip 2:00–3:00 AM): assert the calculator skips the missing slot and returns the next valid occurrence per the job's configured DST-skip policy. For the fall-back night (2:30 AM occurs twice): assert the calculator returns a timestamp on the correct (first or second) side of the ambiguity per the job's configured disambiguation policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.58,"Integration":0.37,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Engine applies missed-run policy (skip or backfill) when the computed next run time has already passed","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is in the policy-evaluation logic — given a scheduled timestamp and a current timestamp, does the engine choose skip or backfill according to the configured policy? This is deterministic conditional logic in one function. REAL-INFRA: No I/O needed; inject fixed past/current timestamps. MOCK-HIDE: No dependencies that would hide the real failure if mocked. INTEGRATION-CHECK (down-test): Call the engine's missed-run handler with a crafted scheduled time (in the past) and a current time, along with the policy config. The failure reproduces in a single function call. Unit is correct.","test_description":"Call the missed-run handler directly with: (a) a scheduled time 10 minutes in the past + policy=SKIP → assert the job is skipped and no backfill is enqueued; (b) a scheduled time 10 minutes in the past + policy=BACKFILL → assert a backfill run is enqueued with the original scheduled timestamp; (c) multiple missed windows (e.g., engine was down for 3 intervals) + policy=BACKFILL → assert all missed runs are enqueued in order; (d) scheduled time in the future → assert neither skip nor backfill is triggered.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9692,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9692},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f792bb66-b562-4d4b-9bb2-19100ff5da4a","uuid":"29409438-9c5b-47fc-a1ed-4781013bcd30"}
